│  https://medium.com/@bavicnative/what-is-gitops-understanding-argocd-fluxcd-15544b36f80d Published Time: 2025-03-31T18:12:30Z         │
│  Markdown Content: [![Image 1:                                                                                                        │
│  Bavithran](https://miro.medium.com/v2/da:true/resize:fill:64:64/0*MvMOWwolBTtnShPn)](https://medium.com/@bavicnative?source=post_pa  │
│  ge---byline--15544b36f80d---------------------------------------) 3 min read Mar 31, 2025 -- Press enter or click to view image in   │
│  full size ## Introduction: From Manual Deployments to Declarative Automation In traditional CI/CD workflows, deployments often       │
│  involve pipelines pushing changes directly to clusters. But this can get messy — version drift, lack of audit trails, and manual     │
│  overrides cause real headaches. That’s where **GitOps** comes in. GitOps is a powerful approach that uses **Git as the single        │
│  source of truth for infrastructure and application deployments**. Instead of pushing code to your cluster, your cluster **pulls      │
│  desired state from Git**, ensuring consistency, traceability, and automated reconciliation. This article explores: * What GitOps     │
│  really means and how it works * The core principles that make it effective * How tools like **ArgoCD** and **FluxCD** implement      │
│  GitOps * Hands-on scenarios with both tools * Pros, limitations, and best practices ## What is GitOps? GitOps is a set of practices  │
│  that combine: * **Git** as the source of truth * **Kubernetes manifests** or Helm charts                                             │
