│      {                                                                                                                                │
│        "topic_title": "Image building and pushing to registry in pipeline",                                                           │
│        "theory_explanation": "One of the most fundamental steps in a containerized CI/CD pipeline for Kubernetes is transforming      │
│  your application code into a runnable container image and then making that image available. This process involves two key actions:   │
│  **building the image** and **pushing it to a container registry**.\n\n1.  **Image Building:**\n    *   This stage uses a             │
│  **`Dockerfile`** – a text file that contains instructions on how to build a Docker image. These instructions specify the base        │
│  operating system, application dependencies, your application's code, and how to run it.\n    *   The CI/CD pipeline executes a       │
│  command (like `docker build`) to create the image based on your `Dockerfile`. For example, `docker build -t my-app:latest .` would   │
│  build an image named `my-app` with the tag `latest`.\n\n2.  **Image Tagging:**\n    *   After building, the image is **tagged**      │
│  with a unique identifier. This tag is crucial for version control and traceability. Common tagging strategies include:\n        *    │
│  `latest`: Points to the most recent successful build (use with caution in production).\n        *   `v1.0.0`: Semantic versioning    │
│  for releases.\n        *   `commit-hash`: Using the Git commit hash for exact traceability.\n        *   `build-number`: A unique    │
│  number generated by the CI/CD system.\n    *   A typical tag might look like `your-registry.com/your-username/my-app:v1.2.3`.\n\n3.  │
│  **Pushing to Registry:**\n    *   Once tagged, the image is **pushed to a container registry**. This registry acts as a central      │
│  repository for all your Docker images. Examples include Docker Hub, Google Container Registry (GCR), Amazon Elastic Container        │
│  Registry (ECR), or your own private registry.\n    *   The CI/CD pipeline uses credentials (often securely managed as secrets) to    │
│  authenticate with the registry and then executes a command like `docker push your-registry.com/your-username/my-app:v1.2.3`.\n    *  │
│  After the image is successfully pushed, the CI/CD pipeline then updates your Kubernetes deployment manifest files (e.g.,             │
│  `Deployment.yaml` or Helm charts) to reference this **newly tagged image**. This ensures that when Kubernetes deploys your           │
│  application, it pulls the correct, most up-to-date version of your image from the registry.\n\nThis automated process ensures that   │
│  every code change results in a new, versioned, and accessible container image ready for deployment.",                                │
