│        "topic_title": "CI/CD pipeline stages for Kubernetes",                                                                         │
│        "theory_explanation": "A CI/CD pipeline isn't just one big magical step; it's a series of carefully orchestrated stages, each  │
│  with a specific job. Think of it like an assembly line for your software. When deploying to Kubernetes, these stages typically       │
│  include:\n\n1.  **Source Stage:**\n    *   This is where it all begins! The pipeline is triggered by a **code commit** to your Git   │
│  repository. The CI/CD system detects the change and starts the process.\n\n2.  **Build Stage:**\n    *   Here, your application's    │
│  source code is compiled (if necessary) and then packaged into a **Docker image**. A `Dockerfile` defines how your application and    │
│  its dependencies are bundled into a lightweight, portable container. This stage ensures your application is ready to run in any      │
│  environment.\n\n3.  **Test Stage:**\n    *   Before deployment, we need to make sure everything works! This stage runs **automated   │
│  tests** – unit tests, integration tests, and sometimes even static code analysis. Catching bugs here, before deployment, saves a     │
│  lot of headaches later.\n\n4.  **Package/Push Stage:**\n    *   Once the Docker image is built and tested, it needs a home. In this  │
│  stage, the newly created Docker image is **tagged** (given a version, like `$v1.0.0` or a unique commit hash) and then **pushed to   │
│  a container registry**. Popular registries include Docker Hub, Google Container Registry (GCR), Amazon Elastic Container Registry    │
│  (ECR), or a private registry within your organization. This makes the image accessible for your Kubernetes cluster.\n\n5.  **Deploy  │
│  Stage:**\n    *   This is where Kubernetes takes center stage! The pipeline uses tools like `kubectl` or **Helm charts** to apply    │
│  your application's configuration (Kubernetes manifests) to the cluster. These manifests tell Kubernetes how to run your              │
│  application, how many copies (pods) to create, how to expose it, and so on. If you're using a GitOps approach (which we'll cover     │
│  later!), an agent within your cluster might *pull* these changes from Git instead of the CI pipeline *pushing* them.\n\nEach stage   │
│  builds upon the previous one, ensuring that only high-quality, tested code makes it to your Kubernetes environment.",                │
