│        "topic_title": "Image Security Scanning",                                                                                      │
│        "theory_explanation": "Imagine you're building a magnificent LEGO castle. Each brick is a piece of software, and the           │
│  instructions are your code. Now, what if some of those LEGO bricks came with tiny, hidden cracks or were made from a weaker          │
│  material? That's what a vulnerable container image is like!\n\n**The Theory:**\nContainer images are the packaged versions of your   │
│  applications, ready to run in environments like Kubernetes. They contain your code, libraries, dependencies, and operating system    │
│  components. Just like any software, these components can have **vulnerabilities** – known weaknesses that attackers could exploit.   │
│  These vulnerabilities are often documented as **CVEs (Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures)**.\n\n**Image security scanning** is     │
│  the process of automatically inspecting these container images for known security flaws, misconfigurations, and compliance issues    │
│  *before* they ever get deployed. It's like having a super-powered X-ray machine for your LEGO bricks!\n\nWhy is this so important,   │
│  especially in CI/CD?\n*   **Preventing Breaches:** A single vulnerable image can open the door for attackers to compromise your      │
│  entire application or even your cluster.\n*   **Supply Chain Security:** Images are built from many layers (base OS, libraries,      │
│  your code). Scanning helps ensure that every part of this \"supply chain\" is secure.\n*   **Compliance:** Many industry             │
│  regulations require you to prove your software is free from known vulnerabilities.\n\n**How it fits into CI/CD:**\nThe best          │
│  practice is to integrate image scanning directly into your CI/CD pipeline. This means that every time you build a new container      │
│  image, it's automatically scanned. If critical vulnerabilities are found, the pipeline can be configured to **fail the build**,      │
│  preventing the insecure image from ever reaching production. Tools like Trivy, Clair, and Snyk are widely used for this purpose.     │
│  You can also integrate scanning at runtime or as part of admission control in Kubernetes, ensuring that only trusted images are      │
│  allowed to run.\n\n**Difficulty Rating:** Easy",                                                                                     │
