│      {                                                                                                                                │
│        "topic_title": "Creating and customizing Helm Charts",                                                                         │
│        "theory_explanation": "Now that you understand the structure of a Helm Chart, let's get practical! You'll often need to        │
│  create new charts for your own applications or customize existing ones to fit your specific needs. Helm provides powerful tools to   │
│  make this process straightforward.\n\n## Creating a New Helm Chart\n\nHelm offers a command to quickly scaffold a new chart with     │
│  the standard directory structure. This saves you from manually creating all the files and directories.\n\nTo create a new chart,     │
│  you use the `helm create` command:\n\n```bash\nhelm create my-new-app-chart\n```\n\nThis command will initialize a new directory     │
│  named `my-new-app-chart` with the following standard structure:\n\n```\nmy-new-app-chart/\n├── .helmignore       # Contains          │
│  patterns to ignore when packaging Helm charts.\n├── Chart.yaml        # Information about your chart\n├── values.yaml       # The    │
│  default values for your templates\n├── charts/           # Charts that this chart depends on\n└── templates/        # The template   │
│  files for Kubernetes resources\n    ├── deployment.yaml\n    ├── service.yaml\n    ├── ingress.yaml\n    ├── NOTES.txt\n    ├──      │
│  _helpers.tpl\n    └── tests/        # A subdirectory for chart test files\n        └── test-connection.yaml\n```\n\n**Key takeaways  │
│  from `helm create`:**\n\n*   **Standardized Start:** It gives you a fully functional, albeit generic, chart right out of the box,    │
│  including basic `Deployment`, `Service`, and `Ingress` templates.\n*   **`tests/` directory:** Notice the `tests/` subdirectory      │
│  within `templates/`. This is where you can define Kubernetes manifests that run tests against your deployed application (e.g.,       │
│  checking if a service endpoint is reachable).\n*   **Overwrite Behavior:** If the destination directory already exists, `helm        │
│  create` will overwrite conflicting files (like `Chart.yaml` or `values.yaml`), but it will leave other existing files                │
│  untouched.\n\n## Customizing Helm Charts\n\nOnce you've created a chart, the real work begins: customizing it for your application.  │
│  This primarily involves modifying the files within the `templates/` and `values.yaml` directories.\n\n1.  **Modifying                │
│  `Chart.yaml`**: \n    *   Update the `name`, `version`, `description`, and `appVersion` to accurately reflect your application and   │
│  chart.\n\n2.  **Customizing `values.yaml`**: \n    *   This file is where you define all the configurable parameters for your        │
│  application. You'll replace the default values provided by `helm create` with ones specific to your application.\n    *              │
│  **Example:** Instead of a generic Nginx image, you'd specify your application's Docker image:\n        ```yaml\n        #            │
│  my-new-app-chart/values.yaml\n        replicaCount: 2\n\n        image:\n          repository: your-docker-repo/your-app\n           │
│  pullPolicy: IfNotPresent\n          # Overrides the image tag whose default is the chart appVersion.\n          tag: \"1.0.0\"\n\n   │
│  service:\n          type: ClusterIP\n          port: 80\n        ```\n\n3.  **Editing `templates/` files**: \n    *   This is where  │
│  you define your Kubernetes resources using Go templating. You'll modify `deployment.yaml`, `service.yaml`, `ingress.yaml`, etc., to  │
│  reference the values defined in `values.yaml`.\n    *   **Example (from `deployment.yaml`):**\n        ```yaml\n        #            │
│  my-new-app-chart/templates/deployment.yaml\n        apiVersion: apps/v1\n        kind: Deployment\n        metadata:\n               │
│  name: {{ include \"my-new-app-chart.fullname\" . }}\n          labels:\n            {{- include \"my-new-app-chart.labels\" . |      │
│  nindent 4 }}\n        spec:\n          replicas: {{ .Values.replicaCount }} # Using a value from values.yaml\n          selector:\n  │
│  matchLabels:\n              {{- include \"my-new-app-chart.selectorLabels\" . | nindent 6 }}\n          template:\n                  │
│  metadata:\n              {{- with .Values.podAnnotations }}\n              annotations:\n                {{- toYaml . | nindent 8    │
│  }}\n              {{- end }}\n            labels:\n              {{- include \"my-new-app-chart.selectorLabels\" . | nindent 8 }}\n  │
│  spec:\n              containers:\n                - name: {{ .Chart.Name }}\n                  image: \"{{ .Values.image.repository  │
│  }}:{{ .Values.image.tag | default .Chart.AppVersion }}\" # Using image values\n                  imagePullPolicy: {{                 │
│  .Values.image.pullPolicy }}\n                  ports:\n                    - name: http\n                      containerPort: {{     │
│  .Values.service.port }}\n                      protocol: TCP\n        ```\n    *   Notice how `{{ .Values.replicaCount }}` and `{{   │
│  .Values.image.repository }}` are used to pull values from `values.yaml`.\n    *   The `include` and `nindent` functions are          │
│  examples of Helm's built-in utility functions that help with templating and formatting.\n\n**Why is this important for               │
│  CI/CD?**\n\nCreating and customizing Helm Charts is a core skill for packaging your applications. In a CI/CD pipeline, once your     │
│  application code is built and containerized, the next step is often to package its Kubernetes manifests into a Helm Chart. This      │
│  chart then becomes the deployable artifact that your pipeline uses to install or update your application on the Kubernetes cluster.  │
│  By leveraging `values.yaml`, you can easily configure your application differently for development, staging, and production          │
│  environments without changing the core chart templates.\n\n**Difficulty Rating:** medium",                                           │
