│      {                                                                                                                                │
│        "topic_title": "Helm Charts structure",                                                                                        │
│        "theory_explanation": "To effectively use Helm, you need to understand its fundamental building block: the **Helm Chart**. A   │
│  Helm Chart is essentially a collection of files that describe a related set of Kubernetes resources, packaged together for easy      │
│  deployment. It's like a blueprint for your application on Kubernetes.\n\nLet's break down the typical structure of a Helm            │
│  Chart:\n\n```\nmychart/\n|-- Chart.yaml          # Information about your chart\n|-- charts/             # Charts that this chart    │
│  depends on (subcharts)\n|-- templates/          # The template files for Kubernetes resources\n|   |-- NOTES.txt       # Optional:   │
│  Instructions for the user after installation\n|   |-- _helpers.tpl    # Optional: Reusable template snippets\n|   |--                │
│  deployment.yaml # Defines your application's Deployment\n|   |-- ingress.yaml    # Defines how to expose your application to the     │
│  outside world\n|   `-- service.yaml    # Defines how to access your application within the cluster\n`-- values.yaml         # The    │
│  default values for your templates\n```\n\nLet's look at each component in more detail:\n\n*   **`Chart.yaml`**: This file is like    │
│  the manifest or passport for your Helm Chart. It contains essential metadata about the chart itself, such as:\n    *                 │
│  `apiVersion`: The chart API version (e.g., `v2`).\n    *   `name`: The name of your chart (e.g., `mychart`).\n    *   `version`:     │
│  The version of your chart (e.g., `1.0.0`). This is crucial for managing updates and rollbacks.\n    *   `description`: A brief       │
│  explanation of what the chart does.\n    *   `appVersion`: The version of the application that this chart installs.\n\n*             │
│  **`values.yaml`**: This is one of the most important files for customization. It defines the *default configuration values* for      │
│  your application. Instead of hardcoding values directly into your Kubernetes YAML files, you use placeholders in your `templates/`   │
│  and define their default values here. For example, you might define the default number of replicas for your application or the       │
│  default image tag to use.\n\n*   **`templates/`**: This directory is the heart of your Helm Chart. It contains all the Kubernetes    │
│  object definitions (like `deployment.yaml`, `service.yaml`, `ingress.yaml`, `configmap.yaml`, etc.) that Helm will render and send   │
│  to your Kubernetes cluster.\n    *   These files are not plain Kubernetes YAMLs; they are **Go template files**. Helm uses a Go      │
│  template rendering engine, extended with Helm's utility functions, to process these files. This allows you to inject values from     │
│  `values.yaml` (or other sources) and use conditional logic, loops, and other powerful templating features.\n    *   `_helpers.tpl`:  │
│  A common practice is to put reusable template snippets (often called \"partials\" or \"named templates\") in this file. This helps   │
│  keep your main template files clean and avoids repetition.\n    *   `NOTES.txt`: An optional file that contains helpful messages     │
│  displayed to the user after the chart has been successfully installed. This can include instructions on how to access the deployed   │
│  application.\n\n*   **`charts/`**: This directory is used for managing **dependencies**. If your application relies on other         │
│  services that can also be deployed via Helm Charts (e.g., a database like PostgreSQL or a message queue like RabbitMQ), you can      │
│  include those charts as \"subcharts\" here. This allows you to manage a complex application as a single, cohesive unit.\n\n**How     │
│  does it work?**\n\nWhen you install a Helm Chart, Helm takes the `templates/` files, combines them with the values from              │
│  `values.yaml` (and any user-provided overrides), renders them into valid Kubernetes YAML, and then sends those YAML manifests to     │
│  your Kubernetes API server for deployment.\n\nUnderstanding this structure is fundamental because it dictates how you define,        │
│  customize, and manage your applications with Helm, which is a core skill for any CI/CD professional.\n\n**Difficulty Rating:**       │
