│      {                                                                                                                                │
│        "topic_title": "Running Docker containers",                                                                                    │
│        "theory_explanation": "---\n\n## Running Docker containers\n\n**Difficulty: Easy**\n\nBuilding a Docker image is like baking   │
│  a cake. Running a Docker container is like serving a slice of that cake – it's an executable instance of your image. A container is  │
│  a live, running process, completely isolated from other containers and your host machine, based on the blueprint provided by its     │
│  image.\n\nThe primary command for running a Docker container is `docker run`. This single command does two things: it *creates* a    │
│  new container from a specified image and then *starts* that container.\n\n**The `docker run` Command:**\n\n```bash\ndocker run       │
│  [OPTIONS] IMAGE [COMMAND] [ARG...]\n```\n\nLet's break down some essential options you'll use constantly:\n\n1.  **`-d` (Detached    │
│  Mode):**\n    *   Runs the container in the background, so it doesn't tie up your terminal. This is typical for server               │
│  applications.\n    *   *Example:* `docker run -d nginx` (runs an Nginx web server in the background)\n\n2.  **`-p` (Port             │
│  Mapping):**\n    *   Maps a port on your host machine to a port inside the container. This allows you to access the container's      │
│  services from your host.\n    *   *Syntax:* `-p <host_port>:<container_port>`\n    *   *Example:* `docker run -d -p 8080:80 nginx`   │
│  (access Nginx running on port 80 inside the container via port 8080 on your host machine)\n\n3.  **`--name` (Name your               │
│  container):**\n    *   Assigns a custom, memorable name to your container. If you don't specify one, Docker generates a random       │
│  name.\n    *   *Example:* `docker run -d -p 8080:80 --name my-web-server nginx`\n\n4.  **`-v` (Volume Mounting):**\n    *   Mounts   │
│  a directory or file from your host machine into the container. This is crucial for persistent data storage (so data isn't lost when  │
│  the container stops) and for sharing configuration files or code during development.\n    *   *Syntax:* `-v                          │
│  <host_path>:<container_path>`\n    *   *Example:* `docker run -d -p 8080:80 -v /my/host/html:/usr/share/nginx/html nginx` (serves    │
│  HTML files from your host's `/my/host/html` directory)\n\n5.  **`-e` (Environment Variables):**\n    *   Sets environment variables  │
│  inside the container. Useful for passing configuration values (like database credentials, API keys) without hardcoding them into     │
│  the image.\n    *   *Example:* `docker run -d -e DB_HOST=mydb -e DB_PORT=5432 my-app`\n\n**Putting it all together:**\n\nA common    │
│  command to run a web application might look like this:\n\n```bash\ndocker run -d -p 3000:3000 --name my-react-app -e                 │
│  API_URL=http://localhost:5000 my-react-image:latest\n```\nThis command:\n*   Runs the `my-react-image:latest` in detached mode       │
│  (`-d`).\n*   Maps host port `3000` to container port `3000` (`-p 3000:3000`).\n*   Names the container `my-react-app` (`--name       │
│  my-react-app`).\n*   Sets an environment variable `API_URL` inside the container (`-e                                                │
│  API_URL=http://localhost:5000`).\n\n**Interacting with Running Containers:**\n\n*   **`docker ps`:** Lists all currently running     │
│  containers.\n*   **`docker stop <container_name_or_id>`:** Stops a running container gracefully.\n*   **`docker start                │
│  <container_name_or_id>`:** Starts a stopped container.\n*   **`docker rm <container_name_or_id>`:** Removes a stopped container.\n*  │
│  **`docker logs <container_name_or_id>`:** Shows the logs from a container.\n*   **`docker exec -it <container_name_or_id> bash`:**   │
│  Executes a command inside a running container. This is incredibly useful for debugging or performing administrative tasks (e.g.,     │
│  getting a shell prompt inside the container). The `-it` flags make it interactive and allocate a pseudo-TTY.\n\nRunning containers   │
│  effectively is a core skill for anyone working with Docker. These commands allow you to deploy, manage, and troubleshoot your        │
│  containerized applications, which is essential for both development and CI/CD operations.",                                          │
