│      {                                                                                                                                │
│        "topic_title": "Building and managing Docker images",                                                                          │
│        "theory_explanation": "---\n\n## Building and managing Docker images\n\n**Difficulty: Easy**\n\nDocker images are the          │
│  fundamental building blocks of containers. Think of an image as a read-only template that contains your application's code, a        │
│  specific runtime (like Python or Node.js), all necessary libraries, dependencies, and configuration files. It's everything your      │
│  application needs to run, pre-packaged.\n\n**Building a Docker Image:**\n\nThe process of creating a Docker image is                 │
│  straightforward and uses the `docker build` command. This command reads the instructions from your Dockerfile (which we just         │
│  discussed!) and executes them sequentially to construct the image.\n\n*   **The Command:**\n    ```bash\n    docker build -t         │
│  my-app:1.0 .\n    ```\n    *   `docker build`: The command to initiate an image build.\n    *   `-t my-app:1.0`: This is the         │
│  \"tag\" for your image. It gives your image a human-readable name (`my-app`) and an optional version (`1.0`). Tags are crucial for   │
│  identifying and managing different versions of your images.\n    *   `.`: This specifies the \"build context\" – the path to the     │
│  directory containing your Dockerfile and any other files your Dockerfile might need to copy into the image. The `.` means the        │
│  current directory.\n\n**Image Layers and Caching:**\n\nA key concept in Docker images is their **layered structure**. Each           │
│  instruction in your Dockerfile (like `FROM`, `RUN`, `COPY`) creates a new read-only layer on top of the previous one.\n\n*           │
│  **Efficiency:** This layered approach makes images incredibly efficient. If multiple images share the same base layers (e.g., `FROM  │
│  ubuntu`), Docker only needs to store those common layers once.\n*   **Caching:** As mentioned in Dockerfile creation, Docker uses a  │
│  build cache. If an instruction and its context haven't changed, Docker reuses the existing layer from a previous build,              │
│  significantly speeding up subsequent builds. This is a huge advantage in CI/CD, where images are built frequently.\n\n**Managing     │
│  Docker Images:**\n\nOnce you've built images, you'll need to manage them. Here are some common commands:\n\n*   **List Images:** To  │
│  see all the images currently stored on your local machine:\n    ```bash\n    docker images\n    # or\n    docker image ls\n          │
│  ```\n    This command shows you the repository, tag, image ID, creation date, and size of your images.\n\n*   **Remove Images:** To  │
│  free up disk space or remove old/unused images:\n    ```bash\n    docker rmi my-app:1.0\n    # or by Image ID\n    docker rmi        │
│  <image_id>\n    ```\n    You cannot remove an image if a container is currently using it. You'd need to stop and remove the          │
│  container first.\n\n*   **Prune Images:** To clean up all dangling (untagged and not referenced by any container) images:\n          │
│  ```bash\n    docker image prune\n    ```\n    You can also prune all unused images (even those with tags but not running             │
│  containers) with `docker image prune -a`.\n\nEffective image building and management are crucial for a smooth CI/CD pipeline. By     │
│  understanding how images are built, layered, and managed, you ensure that your applications are consistently packaged and ready for  │
│  deployment.",                                                                                                                        │
